column168: DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER #5198, OUR PROCESSING PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED A RELEASE OF LIQUID FROM A PLASTIC DRUM THAT WAS TIPPED ON ITS SIDE. column168: AN ASSOCIATE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT WHEN HE DISCOVERED A BOX LEAKING. column168: DRIVER PICKED UP LOADED VAN AND PUT LOAD LOCK IN REAR-DRIVER SAID SIDE WALL OF TRAILER WAS SLICK AND LOAD LOCK CAME LOOSE.  HE STOPPED ENROUTE TO CHECK LOAD AND NOTICED DRIPPING ON SIDE REAR.  HE OPENED DOOR AND A DRUM OF USED ANTI-FREEZE HAD FELL ON ITS SIDE ON TOP OF THE LOAD LOCK.  THE DRUM HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE AND WAS LEAKING. DRIVER CONTAINED SPILL  AND STOPPED LEAK BY OVER PACKING DRUM. DRIVER ALSO NOTICED A DRUM OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL HAD LEAKED AND DRIED AROUND RIM OF DRUM.  APPROX 1 PINT OF ANTI FREEZE LEAKED OUT. LOAD WAS DELIVERED AND TRAILER DECONNED AT SAFETY KLEEN, BATON ROUGE.

column168: AN ARCO TANKER TRUCK/TRAILER HAD BECOME STUCK IN SOFT SHOULDER OF ROAD.  IT WAS NECESSARY TO PUMP OFF THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK BEFORE THE TOW TRUCK COULD PULL IT OUT OF THE MUD.  AFTER PUMPING OUT BOTH COMPARTMENTS OF THE TRUCK, THE HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE UNLOAD HEADER ON THE EMPTY TRUCK.  DRIVER OF PUMP TRUCK WAS INSTRUCTED TO GIVE THE OTHER DRIVER A CAP TO CAP THE OPEN END OF THE HOSE.  THE DRIVER OF THE PUMP TRUCK SUDDENLY DECIDED TO TRY TO DRAIN THE HOSE BACK TOWARDS HIS TRUCK BY PICKING UP THE HOSE AND STANDING U ON THE REAR BUMPER OF THE TANKER.  IN SO DOING, APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT GRAVITY FLOWED BACK TOWARDS THE OPEN END OF THE HOSE BEING HELD ABOVE THE DRIVER'S HEAD.  THE PRODUCT CAME UP OUT OF THE OPEN END OF THE HOSE AT A HEIGHT OF ABOUT 6 FEET AND SPLASHED ON THE BUMPER AND DRAWBAR AND EVENTUALLY ONTO THE SOIL UNDER THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE AFFECTED SOIL WAS DUG UP AND TAKEN BACK TO THE TERMINAL FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED WITH THE OTHER DRIVERS/EMPLOYEES TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE.

column168: FREIGHT WAS CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING CAUSING THE SPILL. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDINGLY TO ALL LOCAL STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN  GIVEN IN CORRECTIVE ACTION FOR THE EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

WHILE MOVING DRUMS THAT WERE IN TEMPORARY STORAGE A DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH THE DRUM GRABBER ATTACHMENT TO THE FORKLIFT. THE RESULT WAS A SPILL INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH THE ABSORBANT WHICH WAS PLACED IN THE OVERPACK WITH THE LEAKING DRUM. THE DRUMS WERE PROCESSED OF BEING RECEIVED AT THE FACILITY LOCATED AT 6125 NORTH PECATONICA IL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 150 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE. THE GENERATOR WILL BE NOTIFIED OF IMPROPERLY IDENTIFIED DRUMS THE FACILITY WILL DISCREPANCY THE MANIFEST AND PROCESS THE WASTE. THE SAFETY KLEEN EMPLOYEE RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS SPILL REVIEWED THE POLICIES FOR MOVING LOADING AND UNLOADING DRUMS WITH HIS SUPERVISOR IN ORDER TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES.

WHILE UNLOADING AT THE FACILITY THE DRIVER NOTICED A DRUM TIPPED OVER IN TRANSIT BECAUSE THE LOAD LOCKS CAME LOOSE. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS WERE SPILLED INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER UPRIGHTED THE DRUM AND PUMPED THE SPILLED MATERIAL BACK INTO THE DRUM AND USED ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP THE RESIDUE. THE ABSORBENT WAS PUT INTO THE SAME DRUM. THE MATERIAL WAS MANAGED AS INTENDED AT THE FACILITY. NO ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE CREATED AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL. THE DRIVER AND THE FACILITY MANAGER REVIEWED THE SOP ON PROPERLY  SECURING HIS LOAD.

THE DRUMS WERE BACK IN THE TRAILER OVERNIGHT, WHERE THEY FROZE CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO EXPAND. THIS EXPANSION CAUSED THE LIDS TO POP OPEN. AS THE DRUMS THAWED A SPILL RESULTED OF APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRUCK. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH PADS AND CONTAINERIZED FOR DISPOSAL. THE DRUMS WERE BROUGHT INTO THE WAREHOUSE AND THE LIDS WERE PUT BACK ON THEM ONCE THEY COMPLETELY THAWED OUT. THE ORIGINAL DRUMS AND THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP WERE SENT TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY, SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEMS INC. 960 TURNPIKE ST. CANTON MA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE STORAGE OF POLY DRUMS OUTSIDE OVERNIGHT DURING WINTER MONTHS WERE THIS PROBLEM COULD REOCCUR IS UNDER REVIEW AND A NEW NAME S.O.P. WILL BE ADOPTED.

WHILE MOVING DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED SPILLING 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED 100 POUNDS OF ADDITIONAL WASTE WHICH WAS SENT ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO SAFETY KLEEN INC.3527 WHISKEY BOTTOM RD, LAUREL MD FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. STORAGE TANK OVER FILL. SPILL CONTAINED IN CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT AREA. RELEASED MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM CONTAINMENT AREA BY VACUM TRUCK AND RE CLAIMED. CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE CLAIMS TO HAVE CALLED CARRIER ON THE 30TH OF DEC BETWEEN THE HOURS OF 9:00 AM AND NOON TELLING A MALE PERSON TO STOP DELIVERIES AFTER THE 31ST AM DELIVERIES AND RESUME NORMAL SCHEDULE ON 01/02-2000.CARRIER HAD NO MALE EMPLOYEES WORKING IN THE PETROLEUM DISPATCH OFFICE DURING THE HOURS OF 9:00 AM NOON ON THE 30TH. NO ONE AT THE CARRIERS DISPATCH RECEIVED THIS CALL. DELIVERIES CONTINUED. DRIVERS UNLOAD IN AN AREA THAT IS 200 YARDS FROM THE STORAGE TANK. THIS STORAGE TANK HAS A CAPACITY OF 998,000 GALLONS AND EXCEPT FOR THE Y2K ISSUE IS NEVER CLOSE TO BEING FULL. CARRIER UNAWARE THAT RAILROAD HAD SHUT DOWN FOR TWO DAYS. ON THE 2ND OF JANUARY DISPATCH ASKED DRIVER TO CHECK STORAGE TANK GAUGE. THIS WAS WHEN OVERFILL WAS DISCOVERED. OVERFILL SHUT DOWN FOR THE STORAGE TANK WAS NOT OPERATIONAL. HAS NOT BEEN WORKING FOR SOMETIME. CAPACITY GAUGE ON THE STORAGE TANK IS UN RELIABLE AND WAS NOT REQUIRED BY THE CONSIGNEE FOR THE DRIVER TO CHECK BEFORE UNLOADING. CONSIGNEE HAS REPAIRED THE OVERFILL SHUTDOWN DEVICE AND IS WORKING ON THE CAPACITY GAUGE. DRIVERS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO CHECK SIGHT GAUGE BEFORE UNLOADING. INVENTORIES FOR THE STORAGE TANK RETURNED TO NORMAL LEVELS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING ON DAMAGED 33 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGED TO THE METAL DRUM WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT. THE FREE PRODUCT CLEANUP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED 33 GALLON METAL DRUM AND ITS CONTENTS AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING ONE DAMAGED 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGED TO THE METAL DRUM WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND GRAY SPONGE TOWEL. THE FREE PRODUCT CLEANUP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON METAL DRUM AND ITS CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

A 55 GALLON DRUM WITH FREE PRODUCT ON THE LID WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1/8TH CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE FREE PRODUCT ON THE DRUM WAS RESIDUE FROM THE DRUM BEING OVER FILLED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE DRUM WAS WIPED OFF, AND WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

APPROXIMATELY A HALF GALLON WAS RELEASED AND DRIED ON THE CARTON. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING . THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION. THE LEAKING PAIL WAS PATCHED UP WITH SOME PUTTY AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE THREE UNAFFECTED PAILS AND TH REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: FARM & HOME ATTEMPTED TO DELIVER HEATING OIL TO A RESIDENTIAL PROPERTY.  THE DRIVER WALKED AROUND THE REAR OF THE PROPERTY AND SAW FILL & VENT PIPE.  HE PULLED THE HOSE AROUND AND BEGAN DISPENSING FUEL; AIR AS COMING FROM THE VENT.  HE BELIEVED IT AS TAKING TOO LONG & STOPPED PUMPING.  WHEN HE CHECKED THE GAUGE, HE FOUND HE HAD PUMPED 386 GAL. THE HOME OWNER HAD FINISHED THE BASEMENT AND IN DOING SO, HE MOVED THE TANK AND THE FILL & VENT ARE NO ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HOME "4" OFF THE GROUND.  THEY WERE COVERED WITH SNOW & NOT VISIBLE TO THE DRIVER AS HE PULLED THE HOSE PAST THAT SIDE OF THE HOUSE.  THE HOMEOWNER NEVER REMOVED OR CAPPED OFF THE OLD FILL & VENT.  AN OPEN DRAIN JUST OUT-SIDE THE DOOR TO THE OUTSIDE STAIRS DISCHARGED THE OIL TO THE RECEIVING STREAM.  J&J  SPILL COMPANY RESPONDED AND WILL BE HANDLING CLEANUP.  DEPT. OF ENVIER.  RESOURCES WAS CALLED & WATERWAY WILL BE MONITORED CONTINUOUSLY WITH BOOMS AND PADS AT THE DISCHARGE AREA AND IN THE STREAM.  FARM & HOME WILL FOLLOW UP WITH INSPECTOR BAUER AT D. E. R. TO COMPLY WITH D.E.R.'S STANDARDS FOR CLEANUP UNTIL FURTHER NOTIFIED BY D.E.R.  HOMEOWNER ARE OUT OF THE RESIDENCE UNTIL CLEANUP IS COMPLETE.  OLD FILL PIPE AND VENT WILL BE DESIGNATED AS "NO FILL" BY SPRAY PAINTING AND SPRAY FOAM SO THAT NO DELIVERY HOSE CAN BE INSERTED INTO FILL PIPE.

BOLTS ON THE FLANGE WERE LOOSE, CAUSING LEAKAGE AT THE FLANGE GASKET.

IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK  CAR WAS NOT COUPLED WHEN IT WAS PLACED ON THE MAIN LINE AND WAS PLACED ON A DOWNHILL GRADE ALLOWING IT TO ROLL OUT. CORRECTIVE PROCEDURES WITH THE CREW TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.

RESPONSE CENTER: REPORT# 517388. 2:30 PM I CALLED MERCER LEPC: THEY DID NOT RESPOND TO MESSAGE TILL 3:00 PM. 2:35 PM I CALLED HARRISON HYDRO SCIENCES FOR SPILL RESPONSE. APPX 3:00 WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP NOTIFIED TO BE ON STAND-BY 4:25 WEAVERTOWN ADVISED ME THEY WERE SENDING A CREW, HOWEVER THEY WERE DELAYED BY WEATHER AND ACCIDENTS COMING FROM PITTSBURGH. AS OF 02-18-00, HARRISON HYDROSCIENCES IS STILL ON SITE OF THIS SPILL.

column168: On January 21, 2000, at 0300 hours, CSX Transportation train # Q33120 pulled into the Flint, MI yard having tank car UTLX 87861 in its train. The train had stopped for the crew to yard. The car was stopped over a switch heater. Tank car was observed on fire at this location. Crew and yard area was evacuated. Fire was confined to the protective housing. T/C was isolated from its train. Appropriate notifications were made. Several outside resources were brought to the site to evaluate options. After careful evaluation it was deciced to conduct a controlled vent and burn. At 0122 hours, January 22, 2000 the incident was over. The entire contents of the t/c had been burned. Evacuation affected approximately 700-1000 people. Release apparently came from a defective valve. A joint investigation included the shipper, valve manufacturers, tank car manfacture, CSX and other interested parties has been formed in order to find the cause of the release.

A damaged five gallon pail was discovered on the dock. Approximately one pint of free product was released. Apparently, the pail was punctured by a forklift. Terminal personnel performed the clean up using absorbent materials. The absorbent materials and clean up materials were placed into a seven gallon recovery drum. The recovery drum will be held along with the damaged pail and remaining product in the terminal hazmat bay awaiting disposition. The remainder of the shipment will be sent on to the consignee. No injuries or exposures were reported. MSDS was requested and received.

THE EMPLOYEE WAS IN THE ACT OF PREPARING THE TANK CAR FOR TRANSFER BY PRESURIZING THE TANKCAR.  THE PRODUCT VALVE ON THE LOADING HOSE WAS THOUGHT TO BE CLOSED AND IT WAS NOT.  THE EMPLOYEE NOTICED PRODUCT STREAMING FROM THE HOSE END AND CLOSED THE PRODUCT VALVE. THE EMPLOYEE  SHOWED LACK OF ATTENTION DURING THIS CRITICAL PROCESS. THE TRAILER HAD NOT YET ARRIVED AND THE HOSE WAS NOT ATTACHED TO THE TRAILER AND THE PRODUCT VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT LEAVE THE PROPERTY, THOUGH THE PRODUCT DID DAMAGE TO THE DRAINAGE SYSTEM.  THE STORMWATER HOLDING TANK HAD TO BE REMOVED AND THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT.  THIS ACTION CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE HOLDING TANK REQUIRING IT TO BE REPLACED.  THE EPA AND IDEM USED WERE NOTIFIED AT THE TIME.  THE INDIANA STATE ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATOR SUPERVISED THE REMEDIATION UNTIL CLOSURE.  THE SPILL WAS DETERMINED TO BE A SPILL OF THREE HUNDRED TWENTY FIVE GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS DISCIPLINED FOR NEGLIGENCE OF JOBS DUTIES AND FAILURE TO FOLLOW WRITTEN JOB INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REPLACEMENT STORMWATER SYSTEM WILL HAVE A DIVERTER VALVE INSTALLED SUCH THAT IN THE CASE OF A SPILL THE VALVE COULD BE OPENED TO DIVERT PRODUCT TO A SEPARATE HOLDING TANK.  THE MANAGER OF THE FACILITY WAS TERMINATED FOR NEGLIGENCE OF JOB DUTIES.

column168: AT 0920 HOURS ON SUNDAY, JANUARY 16, 2000 A SPILL OCCURRED WHILE OFF-LOADING A TANK TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID (VACUUM BLEND #811) AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN (BRIDGEPORT), INC ["SK(BP)"] FACILITY TANK FARM UNLOADING AREA.  PRIOR TO THE INITIAL OFF LOADING OF THE WASTE CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER, THE TANK TRAILER WAS SITUATED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA CAPABLE OF HOLDING SPILLS UP TO 23,683 GALLONS.  THE TANK TRAILER WAS CHOCKED PRIOR TO OFFLOADING.  NITROGEN GAS WAS BEING METERED INTO THE TRAILER AS IT WAS OFF LOADED, SO THAT AN INERT ATMOSPHERE WAS MAINTAINED IN THE TRAILER HEADSPACE.  VALVES ON THE TANK TRAILER WERE OPENED SO THAT WASTE CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER WOULD FLOW THROUGH THE UNLOADING LINE AND PUMPS IN PHASE I. THE WASTE IN THE TRAILER WAS BEING PUMPED THROUGH A HOSE INTO THE UNLOADING LINE AND PUMP IN THE PHASE I TANK FARM FOR STORAGE AND EVENTUAL INCINERATION.  SHORTLY AFTER PUMPING OF THE WASTE INTO PHASE I BEGAN, THE TANK TRAILER ROLLED FORWARD, OVER THE TIRE CHOCKS AND PARTIALLY OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE FORCE OF THE TANK TRAILER MOVING FORWARD RIPPED THE HOSE FROM ITS CONNECTION WITH THE UNLOADING LINE AND PUMP IN PHASE 1. HOWEVER, THIS HOSE REMAINED CONNECTED TO THE TANK TRAILER, ALL OF THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER REMAINED OPEN, AND NITROGEN WAS STILL BEING METERED INTO THE TRAILER HEADSPACE. SINCE THE HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE PHASE 1 TANK FARM UNLOADING EQUIPMENT, AND THE VALVES ON THE TANKER WERE OPEN, WASTE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER  SPILLED OUT OF THE HOSE AND ONTO THE ADJACENT GROUND.  THE TRAILER CONTINUED TO MOVE FORWARD AFTER THE SPILL BEGAN, STOPPING AT THE LIP OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  AS THE TRAILER MOVED FORWARD, THE CONTENTS SPILLING OUT OF THE HOSE WERE RELEASED INTO FOUR MAIN AREAS: THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT SURFACE OF THE TANK FARM UNLOADING AREA, THE TANK FARM PHASE I PUMP PAD, THE ASPHALT ROADWAY EAST OF THE TANK FARM PHASE I AREA, AND ON TO THE SOIL/GRAVEL AREA ADJACENT TO THE SOUTH EAST SIDE OF THE TANK FARM PHASE I AREA.  APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF WASTE LIQUID WERE SPILLED/  THE TANK FARM OPERATOR RESPONSIBLE FOR OFF LOADING THIS TANK TRAILER RESPONDED QUICKLY WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. AT FIRST HE MISTAKENLY THOUGHT SOMEONE WAS DRIVING THE TANK TRAILER OUT OF THE AREA, SO HE RADIOED FOR THE DRIVER TO STOP THE VEHICLE.  WHEN THERE WAS NO RESPONSE FROM THE VEHICLE, HE RAN TO THE CAB TO STOP THE TANK TRAILER.  AFTER THE VEHICLE STOPPED, HE CLOSED THE WASTE UNLOADING VALVES ON THE TRAILER.  AT THIS TIME, PART OF THE TRAILER WAS OUT OF CONTAINMENT, AND THE WASTE UNLOADING VALVES WERE DAMAGED.  SINCE THE VALVES WERE DAMAGED, EVEN THOUGH THE OPERATOR CLOSED THEM, A SMALL AMOUNT OF WASTE CONTINUED TO TRICKLE OUT OF THE DAMAGED VALVES.  THE TANK FARM OPERATOR NOTIFIED THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR OF THE INCIDENT.  AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT THE WIND WAS PREDOMINANTLY BLOWING OUT OF THE EAST FROM THE SPILL AREA TOWARDS THE LABORATORY PORTION OF THE FACILITY.  THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR DECLARED A MINOR EMERGENCY AND

column168: 1. DRIVER PULLED INTO SERVICE STATION TO DELIVER GASOLINE TO UNDERGROUND TANKS.  2. DRIVER HOOKED HIS UNLOADING FITTING TO THE UNDERGROUND TANK FITTING. column168: ON TUESDAY EVENING AT 10:00 I RECEIVE A CALL FROM DISPATCH CONCERNING A SPILL AT THORNTON GAS STATION IN BRADFORD. AFTER TAKING TO DISPATCH AND CALLING A RESPONSE TEAM AND THE DEP. AFTER TALKING TO THE ASSIST CHIEF OF THE BRADFORD FIRE DEPT, I TALKED TO ERIC TO SEE WHAT HAPPEN. ERIC TOLD ME THAT HE ADDED WRONG WHEN HE TOOK THE STICK READINGS. THE STICK READ FOR THE NO LEAD TANK WAS 40, BUT ERIC READ THIS AS 30 INCHES WHICH COMPUTES TO 3322 GALS IN THE TANK. THE TANK IS 91" 12,000 GALLON TANK. ERIC HAD 8700 GALLONS OF NO LEAD ON THE TRUCK TO BE DELIVERED. WHEN YOU ADD3322 GALS AND 8700 GALS YOU COME UP WITH 12022 GALS. ACCORDING TO THIS LOAD WOULD FIT. WHILE DROPPING THE PRODUCT BY SHUTTING HIS INTERNALS. WHILE DROPPING THE GAS ON THE GROUND, ERIC THOUGHT THE GAS WOULD FIT. BY THE TIME HE STOOPED THE FLOW, BETWEEN 10 AND 20 GALLONS OF GAS WAS ON THE GROUND. SOME OF THE GAS WENT INTO A CONTAINMENT BASIN, AND SOME OF THE GAS WENT INTO THE GUTTER OF THE ROAD. THE GAS WENT DOWN THE ROAD ABOUT 250 FEET INTO A FIELD, WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED BY ADYKE THAT THE FIREMAN MADE. AFTER THE RESPONSE TEAM FINISHED CLEANING UP THE SPILL, I BACKED ERIC OUT OF THE STATION AND WENT HOME. WE WILL TALK TO ERIC TOMORROW ABOUT DISCIPLINARY ACTION THAT WILL BE TAKEN.

DENNIS JOHNSON CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER REPORTED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE ON THE "A" END OF THE DOME ASSEMBLY. THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED IN TRACK 805 UNTIL FURTHER REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. STATE FEDERAL AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. ROGER BEATTY FARMLAND INDUSTRIES SHIPPER REQUESTED AND WAS PROVIDED INFORMATION ON THE INCIDENT MR JOHNSON RECOMMENDED TRANSLOADING THE TANKCAR OR POSSIBLY ANOTHER TANKCAR. MR BEATY STATED HE WOULD CONTACT APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL TO CONDUCT THE TRANSLOADING. MR JOHNSON STATED AFTER THE TANKCAR WAS TRANSLOADING IT WOULD BE SENT TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS. column168: FILE 2005 SHIPR:  GRYPHIN, AWB # ZPA 7930686823 ORF, THIS IS A 6800 1 REPORT ONLY.  ON 01/30/2000 AN ODOR WAS  REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE ODOR WAS ON AIRCRAFT N828AX AT GATE9-11 IN BELLY 3 AND 4 PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CHRISTOPHER CHAPPA AND JEFF KIDDER RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A GRAY LIQUID.  THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS AND A FRAGILE HANDLE WITH CARE LABEL.  SIDE 1 OF THE BOX HAD PRE-PRINTED THIS SIDE UP, FREUAD 104 CHICAGO, L, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL, PROPER SHIPPING NAME (PAINT RELATED MATERIAL), UN1283. SIDE 2 & 4 HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS THAT WERE HALF OBSCURED BY TAPE AND PAINT.  SIDE 4 OF THE BOX HAD NOTHING.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD FREUAD CAN COMPANY, CHICAGO, IL 65 LBS.  THERE WERE NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND:  1 METAL 4L RECEPTACLE OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.  THE TOP WAS FOUND TO BE BUCKED, LOOSE AND THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  THIS RESULTED IN THE TOTAL CONTENTS LEAKING OUT.  THE INNER RECEPTACLE HAD MANUFACTURE LABEL AND WAS MARKED "COATING, POLYURETHANE" COMPONENT B.  THE RECEPTACLE HAD STYROFOAM END CAPS AND PACKING PEANUTS.  THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THIS IS ALL THE INFORMATION NOTED DUE TO THE SPILL OBSCURING. THE RECEPTACLE WAS ALSO PACKED INSIDE THE BOX AGAINST ORIENTATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON THE 01/21/2000 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, PAUL SCHMIDT AND MIRANDA SOUTH RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR OF VOMIT.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS FOLLOWS:  THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD AN AIRWAYBILL.  SIDE 1 AND 4 OF THE BOX HAD NOTHING.  SIDE 2 OF THE BOX HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS ONLY.  SIDE 3 OF THE BOX WAS MARKED, BUTYRIC ACID, UN2820, PO111, INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS AND A CARGO AIRCRAFT LABEL ONLY AND A CORROSIVE LABEL.  THE MANUFACTURE SEAL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS GREAT NORTHERN  CONTAINER CORPORATION, 120 LBS., APPLETON, WI.  ALSO ATTACHED TO THE PACKAGE WAS THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND.  1 PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE 11.337 LITERS.  THERE WERE NO NOTED MARKINGS ON THE INNER RECEPTACLE.  THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE AND NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES WERE LOST. ORIENTATION ARROWS, THE WORDS FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. AND LTD QTY.  SIDE 3 OF THE BOX HAD AN ORANGE ROUTE LABEL AND AN INTERNATIONAL LOT LABEL. column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE EAST YARD, LOS ANGELES.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE ITS MANAGER AND DEVELOPED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS ON A INBOUND TRAIN ON YARD TRACK 807.  IT WAS INSTRUCTED TO LEAVE THE CONTAINER IN PLACE UNTIL IT WAS INSPECTED.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY AND OBSERVED THE ABOVE CONTAINER TO BE THE TOP CONTAINER ON DOUBLE STACK CAR DTTX 432029.  AN UNKNOWN LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP CONTAINER ONTO THE BOTTOM CONTAINER, APLU 498321, AND ONTO THE DOUBLE STACK CAR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO "DIAPER" THE TOP CONTAINER AND PLACE IT ON CHASSIS WHERE IT COULD BE MOVED TO LOT 6 FOR INSPECTION.  THE BOTTOM CONTAINER WAS ALSO MOVED TO LOT 6 WHERE IT COULD BE CLEANED OF THE PRODUCT RESIDUE.  FIELD TESTING OF THE LIQUID SHOWED IT TO BE THE SODIUM BISULPHITE SOLUTION LISTED ON THE WAYBILL INFORMATION, LOADED IN WITH OTHER FREIGHT IN THE CONTAINER. THE RAIL CAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE PRODUCT, ALONG WITH THE OTHER AFFECTED CONTAINER.  UPON OPENING THE ABOVE CONTAINER TO LOCATE THE HAZARDOUS DRUMS, NOTED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF 2 X 4'S AND USED PALLETS.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, NOR IS IT APPROVED METHOD FOR THE TRANSPORTATION VIA THE RAILROAD PER THE AAR BOE 6 C.  UPON REMOVING A PORTION OF THE MIXED FREIGHT, LOCATED THE DRUMS CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS PRODUCT.  ONE DRUM WAS FOUND WITH THE BUNG CLOSURE OFF.  IT APPEARS THE CLOSURE WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED WHICH ALLOWED IT TO ROTATE OUT DURING TRANSIT.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 6 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT OF THE DRUM WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THE BUNG WAS REINSTALLED AND PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF ALL RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSED, AND APL FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION WITH THEIR CUSTOMER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE MANAGER, INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, ICTF, LONG BEACH, REPORTING A SUSPECTED LEAKING IM TANK.  MR. POST STATED THE ABOVE IM TANK WAS BEING POSITIONED TO BE PLACED ONTO AN DRAYMANS CHASSIS WHEN THE RAMP DRIVER SMELLED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE IM TANK.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAMP PACKER WAS ISOLATED UNTIL THE IM TANK COULD BE INSPECTED.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE IM TANK AND OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE TANK FRAME WHERE THE DRIP TUBES ARE ATTACHED.  A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR WAS EVIDENT, INDICATING THE LEAK WAS THE IDENTIFIED PRODUCT.  THE DRIP ARE ATTACHED TO THE CATCH BASIN ON THE TOP OF THE IM TANK THAT ALSO HOUSES THE MANWAY. MANAGER COOPER CLIMBED THE REAR OF THE IM TANK, INSPECTED THE MANWAY AREA, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE THAT WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE TANK.  IT APPEARS THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS LOOSE AND VIBRATED OUT WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, AND WAS REINSTALLED.  THE IM TANK WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIME TO ENSURE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED CHEMTREC NOTIFY AIR PRODUCTS, WHO COULD PROVIDE INFORMATION ON THEIR SHIPPING PROTOCOLS, AND IDENTIFY IF THIS PRODUCT REQUIRED A NITROGEN BLANKET PRIOR TO CONTINUING IN TRANSIT.  ROGER PILLOW FROM INTERFLOW, THE OWNER OF THE IM TANK, RESPONDED AND STATED HE WAS UNABLE TO OBTAIN THE PROPER INFORMATION FROM HIS CONTACTS AT AIR PRODUCTS, AND SUGGESTED THE TANK BE ALLOWED TO SIT IN PLACE UNTIL THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE IM TANK WAS REMOVED FROM ICTF AND TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL VENTURA LESBRO FACILITY WHERE IT WILL BE INSPECTED AND THE PRODUCT TESTED FOR CONTAMINATION. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN WHITE ROW STALL 386.  A SMALL POOL LOF DRIED PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON THE PAVEMENT DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF THE CHASSIS WHEELS.  THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND INSPECTED.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, OBSERVED THE WOOD BULKHEAD, WHICH WAS NOT IN CONFORMANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENTS FROM THE AAR PAMPHLET 6C, HOWEVER, APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE TO RESTRAIN THE LADING OF DOUBLE STACKED 55 GALLON DRUMS.  THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS ON THE TOP AND BOTTOM TIER, CONTAINED ONLY 3 DRUMS, WITH CARDBOARD FILLER MATERIAL UTILIZED TO COMPENSATE FOR THE VOID.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR PROPER STOWAGE OF DRUMS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, PER THE AAR PAMPHLET 6C.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH SOLAR INTERNATIONAL, LONG BEACH, WHO REFERRED THE CALL TO SOLAR INTERNATIONAL, NEW ORLEANS, WHO REFERRED THE CALL TO WELLGROW, A FREIGHT FORWARDER, WHO MADE CONTACT WITH CHEMTELL, A PRIVATE RESPONSE INFORMATION COMPANY, WHO MADE CONTACT WITH LOBEL CHEMICAL, NEW YORK, WHO REFERRED THE CALL TO DELTA COMMODITIES, LOUISIANA, WHO REFERRED THE CALL TO HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL, GEISMAR, LOUISIANA. DEVELOPED HUNTSMAN CHEMICAL SOLD THE PRODUCT TO LOBEL CHEMICAL, WHO CONTACTED DELTA COMMODITIES TO LOAD THE PRODUCT INTO THE CONTAINER FOR SHIPMENT.  RECONTACTED LOBEL CHEMICAL AND ADVISED THEM OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING AND THAT THE ENTIRE LOAD WOULD HAVE TO BE INSPECTED IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM(S).  THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED AS THEY CAME OUT.  THREE ROWS INTO THE LOAD, PRODUCT WAS FOUND ON THE FLOORING, AND THE DRUM AGAINST THE LEFT SIDE WALL WAS FOUND AS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE FLOORING HAD BEEN COVERED WITH 1/2 INCH PLYWOOD, WHICH ELEVATED THE FLOOR HEIGHT ABOVE THE SIDEWALL FRAMES OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS ALLOWED THE DRUMS TO MOVE ABOVE AND BEYOND THE FLOOR FRAME AND NEST INTO THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALL WHEN LOADED.  THERE WAS SIDEWALL SECUREMENT 'D' RING WELDED TO THE FLOOR FRAME, RECESSED INTO THE CORRUGATION, THAT THE DRUM RESTED AGAINST.  DURING TRANSIT, THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM RUBBED AGAINST THE 'D' RING, WHICH CAUSED METAL LOSS TO THE CHIME IN 2 PLACES, AND A STRESS CRACK DEVELOPED BETWEEN THE 2 ABRADED AREAS.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WEEPED FROM THE STRESS CRACK.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE PRODUCT, AND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR RETURN SHIPMENT TO THE MANUFACTURER.  ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, WHICH WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE HARBOR FOR VESSEL LOADING.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY BILL KUFFER, MANAGER, INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, LATC, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER KUFFER STATED A DRAYMAN WAS ATTEMPTING TO HAVE THE ABOVE CONTAINER FLIPPED TO ANOTHER CHASSIS WHEN HE OBSERVED AN UNKNOWN LIQUID ON THE CHASSIS FRAME AND DETECTED AN UNUSUAL ODOR.  MANAGER COOPER HAD THE CONTAINER LOCKED DOWN. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE LATC INTERMODAL FACILITY, INSPECTED THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER, AND NOTED LIQUID BYPASSING THE REAR DOOR SEALS. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA WHERE IT COULD BE INSPECTED.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS, OBSERVED RECONDITIONED 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED ACROSS THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  ROPES AND BLOCKS OF STYROFOAM WERE USED TO SECURE THE LADING.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE STYROFOAM WAS DISTORTED AND APPEARED TO BE MELTING FROM THE VAPORS WITHIN THE CONTAINER.  SEVERAL OF THE VISIBLE LABELS ON THE DRUMS SHOWED THE PRODUCT TO BE A TURPENTINE SUBSTITUTE, HOWEVER THE DRUMS HAD NO ADDITIONAL MARKINGS OR LABELS.  INSPECTION OF THE PAPERWORK SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO GENERAL FREIGHT AND THE CONTAINER HAD NO PLACARDS.  CONTACT WITH APL DEVELOPED THE CONTENTS TO VARIOUS MIXED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  CONTACT WITH MEDITERRANEAN SHIPPING, IRVINE, WHO WAS HANDLING THE MOVEMENT OF THIS CONTAINER FROM GREECE, DEVELOPED THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PICK UP ORDER, WHICH WAS FAXED AS A REFERENCE DOCUMENT.  THE PICKUP ORDER SHOWED VARIOUS COMMODITIES AS CORROSIVE, POISON, FLAMMABLE, AND NON FLAMMABLE GAS.  UPON INVESTIGATING THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, THE DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  ONE DRUM ON THE TOP TIER, SECOND ROW IN, WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE DRUM HAD RUBBED AGAINST AN ADJACENT DRUM, WHICH WORE THE METAL AT THE TOP ROLLING HOOP.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, IDENTIFIED AS TURPENTINE SUBSTITUTE, WAS LOST.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK TO SECURE IT.  WHILE UNLOADING TH DRUMS, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE DRUMS HAD NO BILEVEL SEPARATION, AND WERE SITTING ON TOP OF EACH OTHER.  OF THE 16 DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD, 7 WERE IDENTIFIED AS NON REGULATED, AND 9 WERE IDENTIFIED AS REGULATED COMMODITIES, NONE OF WHICH WERE PROPERLY MARKED.  SEVERAL OF THE DRUMS BORE NO IDENTIFICATION MARKINGS.  DIRECTLY BEHIND THE DRUMS WERE COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS (126 POUNDS) MIXED IN WITH SMALLER CYLINDERS (30 POUNDS BOTTLES). THE SMALLER BOTTLES WERE PACKAGED IN CARTONS AND IDENTIFIED AS CHLORDIFLUOROMETHANE, WHICH WAS LISTED ON THE PICK UP ORDER.  THE LARGER CYLINDERS WERE NOT IDENTIFIED ON THE PICK UP ORDER.  AT THIS POINT THE UNDAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER, AND IT WAS SECURED FOR THE EVENING.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH GM IMPORT REQUESTING A LIST OF THE COMMODITIES ON BOARD THE CONTAINER.  COPIES OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION WAS ALSO OBTAINED, AND SEVERAL ITEMS WERE INCORRECTLY IDENTIFIED.  GM IMPORT STATED THE COAST GUARD HAD ISSUED A NOTICE TO REM
